/**
 * @param {TreeNode} root
 * @param {number} limit
 * @return {TreeNode}
 */
var sufficientSubset = function(root, limit) {
    if(!root) return null;
    if(!root.left && !root.right) {
        if(root.val < limit) return null;
        return root;
    }
    root.left = sufficientSubset(root.left, limit - root.val);
    root.right = sufficientSubset(root.right, limit - root.val);
    if(!root.left && !root.right) return null;

    return root;
};
```


    The algorithm solves this problem by recursively checking each node in the binary tree for any insufficient children. If a node is insufficient, we want to remove it from the tree. We start by checking whether a node has any children - if not, it's a leaf node and should be checked for insufficiency. Then, we return either the node if it's sufficient, or `null` if it's not.

Next, we recursively check both the left and right children of a node, pruning the tree by updating their references with their sufficient children. If a node's left and right children are both `null`, it means they were insufficient and the node itself should also be checked for insufficiency. If it's insufficient, we return `null`, otherwise, we return the node.

By going through the binary tree recursively we effectively remove any insufficient nodes and return the root of the modified tree.

